1984- , Uppsala universitet, Statsvetenskapliga institutionen']}, 'dcDescription': ['

It is often suggested that the distinguishing characteristic of public opinion in contemporary Western societies is a lack of shared moral guidelines in life: everything goes. The only ideal left is what is often called individualism, namely that of not accepting any given roles, values or ideals in life but instead striving towards being as free as possible to behave as one pleases. In the thesis that this chapter forms a part of, I offer a different understanding of the much discussed culture of individualism. In later chapters, I shall present data that allow us to question existing assumptions regarding the empirical nature of individualistic values. In this chapter, however, I begin by addressing what I believe is still an un-settled issue of just as much, if not even more, importance: the concept of individualism and how to define it. This chapter aims to equip us with the theoretical Wellingtons we need before venturing into the empirical swamp of individualism. We still know too little about individualism as a set of moral ideals concerning how human beings and society ought to behave. The root of the problem, I suggest, is that we lack a theoretically sound definition of what this kind of normative individualism is and what it is not; which in turn means we have no existing framework for making systematic comparisons between different versions of individualistic ideals. Here, I develop a definition of normative individualism and such a framework. \xa0In doing so, I\xa0do not only contribute to a more thorough understanding of individualism, but also to two closely related debates in political theory. Normative individualism, it is shown, amounts to valuing individual liberty of different kinds. Thus, the concept of individualism provides a new and rewarding entry to two classic conceptual questions which I also discuss: how to define freedom and how to define moral autonomy.

', 'Presented at the Nordic Network in Political Theory, 8th Annual workshop, Uppsala, Sweden, October 2008.', '

'dataProvider': ['Nordic Museum Foundation'], 'dcCreator': ['Lucas, Film', 'Lucas, Film'], 'dcCreatorLangAware': {'def': ['Lucas, Film'], 'en': ['Lucas, Film']}, 'dcDescription': ['Inventering Sesam 1996-1999: Rymdskepp i grå plast. Triangelformad, mitt på förarhytt med öppningsbar lucka under vilken det finns 2 säten. (Två Stjärnornas krig-figurer kan placeras där.) På var sida en lång laserkanon, den högra lös. Bakom förarhytten mörkgrått vridbart harpungevär med lös pil, snöre och en grå kub (vilken troligen har kunnat fästas på batteriluckan). På flera ställen påklistrade originaletiketter i grått och rött/vitt. På bakre högra sidan plats för 2 st 1,5 volts batterier (som har gjort att laserkanonerna har lyst och rymdskeppet låtit), luckan till batteriutrymmet saknas. Under skeppet skjutbar lucka med ett utfällbart grått stöd. (Luckan går nu ej att stänga, stödet löst.) Undertill märkt "c (i ring, copyrightmärke) LUCAS FILM LTD (LFL) 1980 KENNER PRODUCTIONS CINCINATI, OHIO 45202 No 39610". Rymdskeppet är tillverkat efter förebild från biofilmen och TV-serien "Stjärnornas Krig" som kom till Sverige från USA i slutet av 1970-talet. Där heter detta rymdskepp "Snowspeed". Serien, som är en science fiction, utspelar sig i rymden där de goda, rebellerna med t ex Han Solo, Prinsessan Leia Organa, Luke Skywalker, Chewbacka the Wookie, R2 D2 (som är en robot) m fl, strider mot de onda, Rymdimperiet, med Darth Wader i spetsen. Se även inv.nr. 312.864-312.868 och 312.941. Har tillhört Stefan Stålgärde, Jordbro. Inköpt i samband med 1986 års hemundersökning, SAMDOK:s hempool. /Leif Wallin 1996', "Inventory Sesam 1996-1999: Space Ships in grey plastic. Triangle shaped, in the middle of a driver’s cab with opening slot under which there are 2 seats. The two stars' war figures can be placed there.) On each side a long laser cannon, the right loose. Behind the driver’s cab dark grey swivel rifle with loose arrow, string and a gray cube (which could probably have been attached to the battery lid). In several places, original labels applied in grey and red/white. On the back right side place for 2 pcs 1.5 volts batteries (which have made the laser cannons have shone and the spacecraft sounded), the gap to the battery compartment is missing. Under the ship a sliding hatch with a precipitable grey support. (The Luck is now unable to close, the support resolved.) Underneath marked “c (in ring, copyright mark) LUCAS FILM LTD (LFL) 1980 KENNER PRODUCTIONS CINCINATI, OHIO 45202 No 39610.” The spacecraft is made by a model from the cinema and TV series “The War of the Stars” which came to Sweden from the USA in the late 1970s. This spacecraft is called “Snowspeed.” The series, which is a science fiction, plays out in space where the good ones, the rebels with Han Solo, Princess Leia Organa, Luke Skywalker, Chewbacka the Wookie, R2 D2 (who is a robot) m fl, contradict the evil ones, the Space empire, with Darth Wader at the forefront. See also inv.nr. 312.864-312.868 and 312.941. Has belonged to Stefan Stålgärde, Jordbro. Purchased in connection with the 1986 home survey, SAMDOK’s home pool.
